explanation: OS_CHECK_POINTER - determines early return behavior for a NULL sock_id; removing it could change observable behavior (function may continue with a NULL pointer). OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew - allocates the new object/token and (per comment) locks the object type; its success/failure and side-effects (locking) control whether the inner block executes and are therefore relevant to whether that code is dead. LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE - argument to OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew; needed to know if allocation is actually performed for this object type (affects execution and side-effects). OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET - maps token to the internal stream record; required to determine whether writing into the returned record affects program state or is redundant. OS_stream_table - the global table from which the stream record is obtained; its layout/semantics influence whether accesses are meaningful. OS_stream_internal_record_t - the structure being zeroed and written to (fields socket_domain/socket_type); needed to know if these fields are ever used (e.g. by OS_SocketOpen_Impl) so the writes are not dead. OS_object_token_t - the token type passed to OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew/Finalize; needed to understand lifetime/aliasing/side-effects related to token usage. OS_SUCCESS - constant compared against return_code to decide control flow; required to know whether the branch is reachable. memset - the call that zeroes the record; must be inspected to determine if it is redundant (dead) or required for initialization. OS_SocketOpen_Impl - the OS-specific implementation called after populating the record; crucial to know whether it reads the stream fields or token (if it does, the earlier writes are not dead). OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew - finalizes the new object, unlocks the table and stores the public sock_id; its side-effects (unlocking, assigning *sock_id) are essential to observable behavior, so must be analyzed to determine whether preceding operations are necessary.
